✨Design Tip✨

Bold colors and patterns are trending in home design right now, and we will continue to see this trend cross into tile design as well! Patterned tile can become a visual focal point, while more neutral colors can keep the tile from becoming busy or overpowering.

Back in the 19th Century, the French invented the 'gossip' or 'conversation chair'. Essentially an S-shaped seat that sat centrally in a space, and where two people could sit side-by-side and face-to-face and swap news, it was considered the height of sophistication, and was de rigueur in living spaces for decades.

Over time, its popularity waned – as did the looser conversational seating layout it spawned, where armchairs and couches faced each other across a coffee table. Obviously, the advent of the TV into our living rooms can no doubt take the blame for that, with viewing rather than conversing becoming the focus of our down time.

However, interior designers are reporting that more and more of their clients are asking for 'conversational seating' again. And we are so here for it.

-excerpt taken from Jessica Salter for Home & Garden

✨Design Tip✨

Bookshelves can take up a good chunk of real estate in your home and when they do, they become a focal point. They demand attention.

Here are some rules of thumb:

1.Make it substantial.
Before you get to work on how to style your bookcase, consider the placement of your bookshelves themselves - and the scale of them for your room.

2. Don’t stuff it full.
Even if you have lots of books and/or special trinkets to display, try to weed out only the ones you truly love or find another spot for some.

3.Try to find a cohesive color scheme.
Try to find one or two dominant colors to repeat over and over on the bookcase. This will be more soothing to the eye than tons of colors randomly.

4. Ground your bookcase.
Put larger items like boxes or baskets or a stack of large coffee-table books at the bottom. The heaviest things (both physically and visually) should go on the bottom shelves.

5. Use meaningful items.
Have a least one or two objects that are meaningful to you mixed in. Maybe that’s a small piece of art or a couple of photos of family or friends.

💡Design Tip💡

When it comes to hanging art on a wall, ensuring that the artwork is to scale is crucial for achieving a balanced and aesthetically pleasing look. Here are some design tips to help ensure that your art is to scale on a wall:

Measure the wall: Before selecting and hanging your artwork, measure the height and width of the wall where you plan to hang it. This will give you an idea of the available space and the maximum size of artwork that will fit.

Choose the right size: When selecting your artwork, consider the size of the wall and the surrounding furniture or decor. A general rule of thumb is that the artwork should be roughly 2/3 to 3/4 the width of the furniture or decor it is hanging above. For example, if you are hanging art above a sofa that is 6 feet wide, aim for a piece that is around 4-5 feet wide.

Create a mockup: To get a better sense of how the artwork will look on the wall, create a mockup using paper or cardboard cutouts in the same size as the artwork. This will allow you to experiment with different placements and see how the artwork fits into the space.

Texture plays a crucial role in interior design, and is an integral part of a designer’s language and methodology. It goes beyond the physical sensations of decor and soft furnishings, encompassing “visual texture” as well, which involves utilizing various materials to inject character and vitality into a space. Therefore, creating texture is an essential aspect of interior design.

⭐️Reasons to design with Brass ⭐️

Brass adds a hint of glam, warms up a space, and complements the natural, earthy tones that people are craving these days.

The beauty of brass is that it can be used with any style; it will look good in a French Provincial interior as well as in a contemporary home.

Mixing metals creates the visual tension needed for an interior to remain interesting and feel current.
